      "rationale": "Software qualification records for Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1 are maintained under a 21 CFR Part 11 compliant quality management system. IQ/OQ documentation confirms correct installation and benchmark suite execution. Achieved level equals required level for Model Risk 3 / Assurance Medium."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from ASME V&V 10 suite reproduced within 1% of analytical solutions.",
      "rationale": "Three ASME V&V 10 benchmark problems (cantilever beam, Hertzian contact, elastic-plastic cylinder) reproduced within 0.4–0.9% of analytical or reference solutions, confirming correct code implementation for the relevant physics classes."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change < 2% between medium and fine mesh; GCI < 5%.",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence study conducted across three refinement levels (coarse: 0.8 mm global, medium: 0.5 mm, fine: 0.3 mm at screw-rod interface). Construct stiffness QoI changes 1.3% from medium to fine; GCI estimated at 1.8%. Discretization error deemed acceptable."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Nonlinear solver residual convergence to 1e-4 force norm; energy criterion 1e-6 for all load steps.",
      "rationale": "All 11 simulation runs converged to force residual norm < 1e-5 and energy criterion < 1e-7 across all load increments. No divergence events or cutback counts exceeding 3 per load step were observed. Solver error contribution to QoI uncertainty estimated < 0.5%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent model review by second analyst; documented simulation plan reviewed and approved prior to execution.",
      "rationale": "A documented simulation plan was reviewed and approved by a second qualified analyst before execution. Post-simulation independent check confirmed boundary condition application, material assignment, and contact pair definitions. No use errors identified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Linear elastic-plastic model with isotropic hardening validated for Ti-6Al-4V at quasi-static rates; contact formulation captures screw-rod interface behavior.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening model for Ti-6Al-4V parameterized from tensile coupon data (E=114 GPa, σ_y=880 MPa, E_t=1.2 GPa). Augmented Lagrange contact at screw-rod and rod-set-screw interfaces captures load transfer physics. Model form adequacy supported by prior FDA validation studies on comparable spinal implant geometries."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties derived from lot-specific tensile coupon testing; geometry from calibrated CMM measurements; torque-preload from calibrated torque wrench records.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties measured from three tensile coupons per material lot (CV < 3%). Screw and rod geometry verified by CMM with 5 µm resolution. Set-screw torque-preload relationship characterized by strain-gauged rod calibration experiment. Input uncertainty propagated through Monte Carlo (N=1000) confirming QoI sensitivity within bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 constructs from production lots; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to drawing tolerances.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from production lots. CMM inspection of 3 screws per lot confirmed dimensional conformance. Constructs distributed across two independent laboratories (Lab 1: n=6, Lab 2: n=5) to assess inter-laboratory variability."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span clinically relevant range of loading rates and fixture configurations per ASTM F1717.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single ASTM F1717 static compression-bending configuration (5 mm/min crosshead speed, standard UHMWPE blocks). While this matches the regulatory standard, only one loading rate and one fixture geometry were evaluated. The achieved level is 2 rather than 3 because no dynamic or alternative fixture configurations were included, limiting generalizability of the validation evidence to the single tested condition."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions, torque preload) match experimental conditions within measurement uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Simulation geometry derived from CMM measurements of test articles. Material properties from same production lots as test constructs. Boundary conditions replicate ASTM F1717 fixture kinematics. Set-screw torque preload applied in simulation to match experimental torque records (±0.05 N·m). Equivalency confirmed by sensitivity analysis showing QoI variation < 1.5% across input uncertainty range."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 and percent difference < 10% for all three QoIs across all specimens.",
      "rationale": "All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) satisfy E/uval < 1.96 and percent difference < 10% for all N=11 constructs. Maximum E/uval observed: 1.12 (yield force). Maximum percent difference: 9.4% (yield force, specimen 7). Comparison methodology follows ASME V&V 40 Section 5.3 quantitative validation metric framework."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to the COU decision metrics and regulatory submission requirements.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three primary metrics specified in ASTM F1717 and referenced in FDA guidance for spinal implant 510(k) submissions. Each QoI maps directly to a clinically meaningful failure mode (excessive flexibility, permanent deformation, catastrophic fracture). QoI relevance to COU is high."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities use the same device design, loading mode, and regulatory test standard as the COU; no extrapolation beyond validated domain required.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities directly replicate the COU: identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design, ASTM F1717 compression-bending loading, and production-representative material lots. No geometric or loading extrapolation is required to apply validation conclusions to the COU. Inter-laboratory testing at two independent facilities further strengthens relevance."
    }
  ],
